(41, 1, 21, 42, 4, 16, 16, 'on the sabbath day', 'Sabbath Synagogue Teachings', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' practice of teaching in the synagogue on the Sabbath. This connection highlights the significance of the Sabbath as a time for instruction and worship in his ministry.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 22, 40, 7, 28, 29, NULL, 'Authority in Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize the astonishment of the people at Jesus'' doctrine. They highlight that he taught as one having authority, contrasting him with the scribes.', 'parallel', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 22, 40, 13, 54, 54, 'astonished', 'Authority and Astonishment in Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize the astonishment of the listeners at Jesus'' teaching. In Mark, the people are amazed at his authority, while in Matthew, they question the source of his wisdom and mighty works.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 22, 42, 4, 32, 32, 'astonished at his doctrine', 'Authority and Power in Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize the astonishment of the listeners at Jesus'' teaching. Mark highlights his authority, while Luke notes that his word was with power, suggesting a shared theme of impactful teaching.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 22, 24, 23, 29, 29, 'taught them as one that had authority', 'Authority and Power of God''s Word', 'This connection highlights the authority of Jesus'' teaching in Mark, which parallels the powerful imagery of God''s word in Jeremiah. Both passages emphasize the transformative and impactful nature of divine communication.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 22, 42, 21, 15, 15, 'taught them as one that had authority', 'Authority and Wisdom in Teaching', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority in teaching. Both passages emphasize the ability to speak with wisdom that cannot be resisted, showcasing a divine empowerment in communication.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 22, 43, 7, 46, 46, 'taught them as one that had authority', 'Authority in Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize the unique authority of Jesus'' teaching. In Mark, the astonishment at His doctrine reflects a distinctiveness that is echoed in John, where the officers note that no one spoke like Him.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 22, 44, 6, 10, 10, 'taught them as one that had authority', 'Authority and Wisdom in Speech', 'Both passages emphasize the remarkable authority and wisdom in speech. In Mark, Jesus teaches with authority, while in Acts, the speaker''s wisdom and spirit are unresistable.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 23, 41, 9, 25, 25, 'unclean spirit', 'Connection of Unclean Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' authority over unclean spirits. In Mark 1:23, the unclean spirit''s presence is highlighted, while Mark 9:25 shows Jesus rebuking a foul spirit, demonstrating His power to cast them out.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 23, 40, 12, 43, 43, 'unclean spirit', 'Connection of Unclean Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of ''unclean spirit'' and its actions. Mark describes a man with an unclean spirit, while Matthew discusses the actions of an unclean spirit after leaving a man.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 23, 41, 1, 34, 34, NULL, 'Healing and Exorcism Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of casting out devils, linking the presence of unclean spirits with Jesus'' healing ministry. The unclean spirit''s cry in the synagogue foreshadows the broader context of Jesus'' authority over evil in the subsequent healing of many.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 23, 41, 5, 2, 2, 'a man with an unclean spirit', 'Connection of Unclean Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of a man with an unclean spirit. This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' authority over unclean spirits in different locations.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 23, 41, 7, 25, 25, 'unclean spirit', 'Connection of Unclean Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of an unclean spirit affecting individuals. The man in the synagogue and the woman''s daughter both illustrate the struggle against unclean spirits in their respective contexts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 23, 42, 4, 33, 37, 'a man with an unclean spirit', 'Connection of Unclean Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize a man with an unclean spirit who cries out in a synagogue, showcasing Jesus'' authority over evil. The similar phrasing and context highlight the significance of Jesus'' power in confronting unclean spirits.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 24, 40, 8, 29, 29, 'art thou come to destroy us', 'Demons Recognizing Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the demons'' recognition of Jesus'' identity and authority. They express fear of His power to torment them, highlighting a common theme of spiritual confrontation.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 24, 59, 2, 19, 19, NULL, 'Recognition of Jesus'' Authority', 'This connection highlights the acknowledgment of Jesus'' identity as ''the Holy One of God'' in Mark, paralleling James'' assertion that even ''the devils also believe.'' Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus'' divine nature and the fear it instills.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 24, 42, 4, 34, 34, 'the Holy One of God', 'Connection of Demonic Recognition', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus as ''the Holy One of God'' by a demon. This shared phrase highlights the authority and identity of Jesus in confronting evil spirits.', 'keyword', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 24, 44, 3, 14, 14, 'the Holy One of God', 'Connection of the Holy One', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of Jesus as ''the Holy One.'' In Mark, a demon acknowledges Jesus'' divine nature, while in Acts, Peter refers to Jesus as ''the Holy One and the Just,'' contrasting Him with a murderer.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 24, 66, 3, 7, 7, 'the Holy One of God', 'Holiness of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus'' holiness in both passages. In Mark, Jesus is called ''the Holy One of God,'' while in Revelation, He is referred to as ''he that is holy.''', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 24, 41, 5, 7, 7, 'what have we to do with thee', 'Demons Recognizing Jesus'' Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the demons'' recognition of Jesus'' identity and authority. They express fear and a desire to avoid torment, highlighting their awareness of His power as the Holy One of God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 24, 42, 8, 28, 28, NULL, 'Demons Recognizing Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus by demons, highlighting their awareness of His divine authority. The phrases ''what have I to do with thee'' and ''torment me not'' reflect their fear and acknowledgment of His power.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 25, 41, 1, 34, 34, 'come out of him', 'Authority Over Demons', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' authority over demons. In Mark 1:25, Jesus commands a demon to come out, while in Mark 1:34, he casts out many devils and prevents them from speaking, showcasing his power and control over evil spirits.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 25, 41, 3, 11, 12, 'come out of him', 'Authority Over Unclean Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' authority over unclean spirits. In Mark 1:25, Jesus commands a spirit to come out, while in Mark 3:11-12, unclean spirits recognize him as the Son of God and submit to his authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 25, 42, 4, 41, 41, NULL, 'Authority Over Demons', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' authority in rebuking demons. In Mark, Jesus commands silence and expulsion, while in Luke, he similarly rebukes demons to prevent them from speaking.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 25, 44, 16, 17, 17, NULL, 'Authority Over Spirits', 'This connection highlights the authority of Jesus and Paul over spiritual entities. In both passages, there is a demonstration of power where Jesus commands silence and departure, while Paul is acknowledged as a servant of God, indicating a similar authority in proclaiming salvation.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 25, 42, 4, 35, 35, 'Hold thy peace, and come out of him.', 'Connection in Jesus'' Rebuke', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' authority over demons through the phrase ''Hold thy peace, and come out of him.'' This connection highlights the consistency in Jesus'' command and the immediate response of the unclean spirit.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 25, 19, 50, 16, 16, 'Hold thy peace, and come out of him', 'Authority Over Wickedness', 'This connection highlights the authority of Jesus in rebuking evil, paralleling God''s challenge to the wicked in Psalm 50. Both passages emphasize the separation between the righteous and the wicked regarding divine matters.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 26, 41, 9, 26, 26, 'and cried with a loud voice', 'Connection of Unclean Spirit Exorcisms', 'Both passages emphasize the dramatic expulsion of an unclean spirit, highlighting the violent nature of the spirit''s departure. The phrases ''cried'' and ''rent'' in both verses illustrate the intensity of the exorcism experience.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 26, 41, 9, 20, 20, NULL, 'Connection of Unclean Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize the violent reaction of the unclean spirit when confronting Jesus. The phrase ''tore him'' in both instances illustrates the torment inflicted on the possessed individuals.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 26, 42, 9, 39, 39, NULL, 'Connection of Unclean Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize the violent actions of the spirit as it departs from the afflicted individual. The phrases ''teareth him'' and ''torn him'' highlight the struggle during the exorcism process.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
